  "local_port": 46918,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What is smart strategy to prepare for CMAT 2017?",
  "response": "Preparing for the CMAT (Common Management Admission Test) 2017 requires a strategic approach to maximize your score. Since CMAT tests your aptitude in **Quantitative Techniques, Logical Reasoning, Language Comprehension, and General Awareness**, here\u2019s a smart strategy to ace the exam:\n\n---\n\n### **1. Understand the Exam Pattern and Syllabus**\n- **Duration**: 180 minutes\n- **Sections**:  \n  - Quantitative Techniques & Data Interpretation (20 questions)  \n  - Logical Reasoning (20 questions)  \n  - Language Comprehension (20 questions)  \n  - General Awareness (20 questions)  \n  - Innovation & Entrepreneurship (20 questions)  \n- **Marking Scheme**: +4 for correct answers, -1 for incorrect answers.\n\n**Action Plan**: Familiarize yourself with the syllabus and weightage of topics in each section to prioritize preparation.\n\n---\n\n### **2. Create a Study Plan**\n- Allocate time to each section based on your strengths and weaknesses.  \n- Dedicate more time to weaker sections but don\u2019t neglect strong areas.  \n- Practice daily with a mix of theory, concepts, and mock tests.  \n\n**Sample Weekly Plan**:  \n- **Monday**: Quantitative Techniques (focus on Arithmetic, Algebra, Geometry).  \n- **Tuesday**: Logical Reasoning (focus on puzzles, arrangements, and syllogisms).  \n- **Wednesday**: Language Comprehension (focus on grammar, vocabulary, and reading comprehension).  \n- **Thursday**: General Awareness (focus on current affairs, business, and static GK).  \n- **Friday**: Mock Test + Analysis.  \n- **Saturday**: Revision of all sections.  \n- **Sunday**: Innovation & Entrepreneurship (focus on case studies and basic concepts).  \n\n---\n\n### **3. Strengthen Basics and Practice Regularly**\n- **Quantitative Techniques**: Focus on basics like percentages, ratios, profit & loss, and time-speed-distance. Practice shortcut methods for faster calculations.  \n- **Logical Reasoning**: Solve puzzles, seating arrangements, and syllogisms regularly. Improve analytical thinking.  \n- **Language Comprehension**: Read newspapers, editorials, and books to improve vocabulary and comprehension. Practice grammar rules.  \n- **General Awareness**: Stay updated with current affairs from the last 6 months. Use apps, newspapers, and GK books.  \n- **Innovation & Entrepreneurship**: Understand basic concepts and practice case study-based questions.  \n\n---\n\n### **4. Solve Previous Years\u2019 Papers and Mock Tests**\n- Take **CMAT 2015 and 2016 papers** to understand the difficulty level and question patterns.  \n- Attempt **mock tests** regularly to improve time management and accuracy.  \n- Analyze your performance to identify weak areas and work on them.  \n\n---\n\n### **5. Time Management Tips**\n- Divide your time equally among sections (approx. 30-45 minutes per section).  \n- Avoid spending too much time on a single question.  \n- Attempt easier questions first and revisit tougher ones later.  \n\n---\n\n### **6. Focus on General Awareness**\n- Since GK plays a crucial role, stay updated with current affairs, business news, and static GK.  \n- Revise important topics like awards, sports, and government schemes regularly.  \n\n---\n\n### **7. Revise and Stay Consistent**\n- Revise formulas, shortcuts, and concepts regularly.  \n- Stay consistent with your preparation and avoid last-minute cramming.  \n- Stay calm and confident during the exam.  \n\n---\n\n### **8. Recommended Books**\n- **Quantitative Techniques**: \"Quantitative Aptitude for Competitive Examinations\" by R.S. Aggarwal.  \n- **Logical Reasoning**: \"A Modern Approach to Logical Reasoning\" by R.S. Aggarwal.  \n- **Language Comprehension**: \"Word Power Made Easy\" by Norman Lewis.  \n- **General Awareness**: \"Manorama Yearbook\" or \"Lucent GK\".  \n- **Innovation & Entrepreneurship**: NCERT books or online resources.  \n\n---\n\nBy following this strategy, you can prepare effectively for CMAT 2017 and achieve a high score. Good luck!",
  "temperature": 1.0,
